<br>
That being said a couple of quotes:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If you take physics and apply it loosely to some of the principals of Wicca, you find it makes more sense than most religions.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Please don't go there.  I study physics.  Every time I end up discussing religeon people start to show my how physics proves their religeon right.  Its annoying, and more often than not based on hugely incorrect understanding of the subject.  I have yet to find a religeon whose beliefs I could not reconcile with almost every physical concept with a little work.  <br>
<br>
Take your own explanation about energy neither being created or destroyed for example.  I know they teach you that in 8th grade, but it is not an entirely accurate statement.  A more accurate statement would be that there is a fundamental symmetry that results in a conservation of energy.  Why is that different than what you stated?  Well, simply put in order for the symmetry to be valid 2 things must happen.  First, you must take into account the entire universe at once - in one small location it is possible to violate the symmetry.  Second, the symmetry must be valid at all points in the universe - this might not be the case in places like Black Holes where our laws of physics break down. Also, electricity is a form of energy - it is not energy.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Makes a little more sense than it burning in this huge furnace. If god is all powerful, and all good, he wouldn't want suffering. You say he gave us free will... fine and dandy. When the morning star fell, and hell was created, why didn't god just cease the devil? He's all powerful, and there is the &quot;war between heaven and hell&quot; if god was all powerful, he'd have simple spoke a word, or thought, or whatever it is he was supposed to have done, and satan would have been wiped out. If he was all merciful and knowing, he wouldn't have let satan exist to bring the suffering upon the planet that he supposedly does.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I love this argument - it is the most hugely self defeating argument brought up when people talk of an omnipotent, omniscient being.  Let me explain.<br>
<br>
Your argument is based on the claim that for God to be good, he would not want pain and suffering.  This is because pain and suffering are &quot;bad&quot;.  Stop for a moment and think about that claim - is pain and suffering really &quot;bad&quot;?  For instance - if there was no sadness could there be joy?  This leads to a requirement that there be opposition in all things.  If God wants his children to be happy - he must allow pain to exist.<br>
<br>
Lets move to a more concrete example - have you ever seen how steel is made?  Steel starts out as iron ore - rather ugly and not terribly usefull.  So, the first thing you do is throw it in a fire and melt it.  They then blow oxygen directly into the melted mix - which causes a chain reaction inside the iron.  The iron is heated even further, and almost all impurities are driven out.  At this point, when the iron is ready to be worked, specific quantities of carbon are introduced back into the iron - creating steel.  Through a process of adverse conditions almost worthless iron ore changes to steel - the foundation of the modern world.<br>
<br>
I could go through the formation of diamond as well to give another example - but it leads to the same conclusion.  Often times, in order for a substance to acheive its full conditions it must pass through adverse conditions first.  Even more to the point, any parent can tell you that sometimes you must let your children experience painful situations in order to save them a larger amount of hurt later on.<br>
<br>
Now, back to God - if he really is all powerful, all knowing, and all good - he knows exactly what we need to be happy, what we need to acheive our full potential, and how to give it to us without removing the opportunity to be happy and grow.  Like any parent, I am sure it hurts him to see us suffer.  However, knowing the end result, he does not interfere with certain things for our own good.<br>
<br>
The argument you presented is fundamentally flawed.  The flaw is really a rather serious one - you are claiming that if God really does know everything and is all powerful - he would act like you want him too.  For that to be true, you have to be all powerful and all knowing - or else I am forced to accept that God might know more than you and what you think he should do is not correct - even if I don't understand why.<br>
<br>
Personally, I think pain and adversity is a part of growth - that we all have flaws that must be worked out for us to reach our potential.  I think the suffering and pain on the earth is a direct result of those same flaws - and that God allows it to continue to give us a chance to work those flaws out.  I believe in a progression - that if we are God's children, like any parent he wants us to grow up to be like him and everything we experience or do on this Earth is directly related to that goal.<br>
<br>
Wicca, Christian, Pagan, whatever - I think you will find all religeons share the fundamental belief that growth requires we identify our flaws and work to overcome them.<br>
<br>
Also, just a side note on the Gaia theory - there are many religeons, including Christian ones, that believe the Earth has a spirit of its own (that in some sense the Earth is a living being).  I know mine does - and I am in a Christian religeon.<br>
<br>
